Er, no idea.

25
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:10,480
I'm going to say Africa, but that's just a guess.

26
00:01:10,480 --> 00:01:14,480
OK, well, I will reveal the answer later in the programme.

27
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:17,920
On a recent edition of BBC Radio 4's The Food programme,

28
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:20,879
there was an interview with Dr. Morgane Gay.

29
00:01:20,879 --> 00:01:22,560
She is a futurologist.

30
00:01:22,560 --> 00:01:28,159
A futurologist is someone who studies and predicts the way we will be living in the future.

31
00:01:28,159 --> 00:01:32,000
Her particular area of expertise is the subject of food.

32
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,799
What two things does she say she thinks about?

33
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:41,280
As a food-futrologist, I think about not just what we're going to be eating in the future,

34
00:01:41,280 --> 00:01:44,719
but why? Why that thing? Why that trend?

35
00:01:44,719 --> 00:01:48,079
Why will people suddenly latch onto that food,

36
00:01:48,079 --> 00:01:51,280
that way of eating that food at that particular time?

37
00:01:51,359 --> 00:01:54,799
And when I work for large companies, that's what they want to know.

38
00:01:54,799 --> 00:01:59,280
There is an element of a hunch, and then proving or disproving that hunch.

39
00:02:00,159 --> 00:02:02,400
So, what two things does she think about?

40
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:09,680
She says that as a food-futurologist, she thinks about what we will be eating in the future,

41
00:02:09,680 --> 00:02:12,639
and also why we will be eating that food.

42
00:02:12,639 --> 00:02:16,080
Yes, in particular, she looks at why there are particular trends.

43
00:02:16,719 --> 00:02:20,719
A trend is what is popular now or what is becoming popular.

44
00:02:20,719 --> 00:02:24,639
For example, at the moment there is a trend for eating less red meat.

45
00:02:25,199 --> 00:02:29,039
She also looks at why people latch onto particular trends.

46
00:02:29,599 --> 00:02:33,439
To latch onto here means to be very interested in something.

47
00:02:34,079 --> 00:02:38,639
So if you latch onto a particular food trend, you start to follow that trend.

48
00:02:38,639 --> 00:02:41,360
You might start eating that particular diet.

49
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:46,079
Information about future trends is very important for companies in the food business.

50
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:49,439
How does she actually predict these trends?

51
00:02:49,439 --> 00:02:51,599
She says she starts with a hunch.

52
00:02:52,159 --> 00:02:55,199
A hunch is a feeling you get that something is true.

53
00:02:55,919 --> 00:03:02,479
You don't have any real evidence, but your experience and knowledge makes you think you might be right.

54
00:03:02,479 --> 00:03:04,000
Let's listen again.

55
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:09,759
As a food-futurologist, I think about not just what we're going to be eating in the future,

56
00:03:09,759 --> 00:03:13,199
but why? Why that thing? Why that trend?

57
00:03:13,199 --> 00:03:16,560
Why will people suddenly latch onto that food,

58
00:03:16,640 --> 00:03:19,759
that way of eating that food at that particular time?

59
00:03:19,759 --> 00:03:23,280
And when I work for large companies, that's what they want to know.

60
00:03:23,280 --> 00:03:27,920
There is an element of a hunch and then proving or disproving that hunch.

61
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:32,879
Dr Gay goes on to talk about how on the subject of food there are restrictions.

62
00:03:32,879 --> 00:03:33,840
Why is that?

63
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:37,759
Food business, of course, has different restrictions around it because it's about safety.

64
00:03:37,759 --> 00:03:42,400
We're ingesting that, the supply chain and the labeling laws are very

65
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:44,480
stringent, especially in this country.

66
00:03:44,480 --> 00:03:50,240
So it takes a lot longer to get an idea from just a concept that's discussed around a table

67
00:03:50,240 --> 00:03:56,000
to an actual production facility labeled, branded, tested, marketed and put on the shelves.

68
00:03:56,719 --> 00:03:58,319
So why restrictions?

69
00:03:58,319 --> 00:04:00,080
Well, it's about safety.

70
00:04:00,080 --> 00:04:06,000
Because we are ingesting food, which is a way of saying we are putting it into our bodies,

71
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:07,599
it has to be safe.

72
00:04:07,599 --> 00:04:11,759
It can be a long process of developing a new food and getting it into the shops,

73
00:04:11,759 --> 00:04:15,359
because of the need to be safe and meet the laws of different countries.

74
00:04:16,159 --> 00:04:20,399
In the UK, she mentions that the food safety laws are very stringent.

75
00:04:20,399 --> 00:04:23,279
This means that the laws are very tough, very strict.

76
00:04:23,279 --> 00:04:24,879
Let's hear Dr Gay again.

77
00:04:25,519 --> 00:04:29,360
Food business, of course, has different restrictions around it because it's about safety.

78
00:04:29,360 --> 00:04:34,639
We're ingesting that, the supply chain and the labeling laws are very stringent,

79
00:04:34,639 --> 00:04:36,159
especially in this country.

80
